00:01:49,350 --> 00:01:53,043
Armenia is a small
land-locked Christian nation

23
00:01:53,078 --> 00:01:56,357
surrounded by mostly
non-Christian neighbors.

24
00:01:56,392 --> 00:02:00,430
Azerbaijan over there,
Iran down there,

25
00:02:00,465 --> 00:02:03,364
and Turkey right there.

26
00:02:03,399 --> 00:02:05,677
Turkey and relations with Turkey

27
00:02:05,711 --> 00:02:07,610
and the Armenian people's
terrible history

28
00:02:07,644 --> 00:02:09,543
with that country
being the central

29
00:02:09,577 --> 00:02:12,891
and defining issue
of Armenian identity

30
00:02:12,925 --> 00:02:15,031
and a present-day
political reality

31
00:02:15,065 --> 00:02:20,485
103 years after what just about
anyone would call genocide.

32
00:02:20,519 --> 00:02:24,213
Turkey has always
adamantly denied that,

33
00:02:24,247 --> 00:02:27,526
saying it was simply
a messy war.

34
00:02:30,909 --> 00:02:33,498
Yerevan is the capital
of Armenia,

35
00:02:33,532 --> 00:02:36,708
a city of about
one million people.

36
00:02:36,742 --> 00:02:38,227
Mount Ararat looms over it,

37
00:02:38,261 --> 00:02:40,988
a cultural touchstone
and a constant reminder

38
00:02:41,022 --> 00:02:44,474
of what was done
on the other side.

39
00:02:49,583 --> 00:02:51,343
Think of Armenia,
and chances are

40
00:02:51,378 --> 00:02:53,759
you think instead
of an Armenian,

41
00:02:53,794 --> 00:02:58,074
maybe someone you know
or maybe someone on TV.

42
00:02:58,108 --> 00:03:01,595
These guys, for instance,
famous Armenians.

43
00:03:01,629 --> 00:03:03,838
We needed an Armenian.

44
00:03:03,873 --> 00:03:06,841
I needed an Armenian
to push me over the edge,

45
00:03:06,876 --> 00:03:08,326
help me find a window,

46
00:03:08,360 --> 00:03:10,224
a lens with which
to look at a country

47
00:03:10,259 --> 00:03:12,951
which, for some reason,
I'd managed to not visit

48
00:03:12,985 --> 00:03:14,780
on my travels.

49
00:03:14,815 --> 00:03:16,782
Then, this guy reached out...

50
00:03:16,817 --> 00:03:20,441
Serj Tankian, front man
for the Armenian-American band

51
00:03:20,476 --> 00:03:22,581
System of a Down.

52
00:03:22,616 --> 00:03:26,344
And the whole thing
started to fall into place.

53
00:03:26,378 --> 00:03:30,279
Serj first visited Armenia
17 years ago.

54
00:03:30,313 --> 00:03:32,384
Since then, he's performed
a number of shows,

55
00:03:32,419 --> 00:03:34,386
including one
with System of a Down

56
00:03:34,421 --> 00:03:38,252
during the centennial
of the Armenian genocide.

57
00:03:38,287 --> 00:03:39,978
We meet up at Dolmama,

58
00:03:40,012 --> 00:03:41,600
his favorite restaurant
in Yerevan,

59
00:03:41,635 --> 00:03:45,294
and right away I identify
a potential problem.

60
00:03:45,328 --> 00:03:47,088
Well, my first question is:

61
00:03:47,123 --> 00:03:48,987
I understand you're
a pescatarian?

62
00:03:49,021 --> 00:03:51,472
- Yeah.
- How does one...

63
00:03:51,507 --> 00:03:54,234
You're like,
"What the fuck are you doing?"

64
00:03:54,268 --> 00:03:55,649
This is a land-locked country

65
00:03:55,683 --> 00:03:57,961
in the heart of, like,
meat on a stick zone.

66
00:03:57,996 --> 00:03:59,998
Well, I'm interested to see

67
00:04:00,032 --> 00:04:01,682
how you navigate your way
through this week.

68
00:04:01,689 --> 00:04:05,175
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Well, we've got amazing trout.

69
00:04:05,210 --> 00:04:07,005
And lots of great veggies.

70
00:04:07,039 --> 00:04:08,731
I'm just busting your balls.

71
00:04:08,765 --> 00:04:10,905
Of course you are.

72
00:04:10,940 --> 00:04:12,907
So how Armenian are you?
I mean...

73
00:04:12,942 --> 00:04:14,005
That's a really good question.

74
00:04:14,012 --> 00:04:15,427
You were born in...

75
00:04:15,462 --> 00:04:17,326
Yeah, I was born in Beirut,
grew up in I.A.

76
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:20,294
I'm Armenian by culture.
Both my parents are Armenian.

77
00:04:20,329 --> 00:04:24,022
My grandparents, you know,
ended up in Syria and Lebanon

78
00:04:24,056 --> 00:04:25,610
because of the genocide.

79
00:04:25,644 --> 00:04:26,956
And how Armenian am I?

80
00:04:26,990 --> 00:04:28,785
That's a really
good question, man.

81
00:04:28,820 --> 00:04:31,167
The majority of Armenians
that live in the Diaspora

82
00:04:31,201 --> 00:04:32,686
didn't voluntarily migrate.

83
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:35,171
You know, they were...
They were forced migrations,

84
00:04:35,205 --> 00:04:37,449
pogroms, you know,
after the genocide.

85
00:04:37,484 --> 00:04:39,064
So they ended up
in the Middle East and Europe

86
00:04:39,071 --> 00:04:40,694
and different parts
of the world.

87
00:04:40,728 --> 00:04:44,698
So, we have this kind
of feeling of being kicked out,

88
00:04:44,732 --> 00:04:48,046
and that longing is different
than other diasporas I think

89
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:49,703
because of that.

90
00:04:49,737 --> 00:04:52,153
Diaspora Armenian communities,

91
00:04:52,188 --> 00:04:54,328
wherever they are,
have been held together

92
00:04:54,363 --> 00:04:56,330
by deep feelings of nationalism

93
00:04:56,365 --> 00:04:58,470
and injustice
for what happened to them

94
00:04:58,505 --> 00:05:03,372
and how the world
refused to acknowledge it.

95
00:05:03,406 --> 00:05:05,477
Dolmama specializes
in modern versions

96
00:05:05,512 --> 00:05:08,238
of Armenian classic dishes.

97
00:05:08,273 --> 00:05:10,344
Khashlama, a braised lamb shank

98
00:05:10,379 --> 00:05:12,312
served with rice pilaf.

99
00:05:12,346 --> 00:05:14,141
It's a big little snack.

100
00:05:14,175 --> 00:05:15,901
That is a leg of...

101
00:05:15,936 --> 00:05:18,904
a leg of lamb,
a little guy, yes.

102
00:05:18,939 --> 00:05:20,906
Yeah.

103
00:05:20,941 --> 00:05:23,737
Wow. It's pretty too.

104
00:05:23,771 --> 00:05:26,705
So manti is like
my grandmother used to make it,

105
00:05:26,740 --> 00:05:28,466
but it looks completely
different than this

106
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:30,226
because this is
vegetarian manti.

107
00:05:30,260 --> 00:05:34,368
They're like little boats
with spices and onions.

108
00:05:34,403 --> 00:05:37,198
You probably thank
Genghis Khan for this.

109
00:05:37,233 --> 00:05:38,579
The dumplings.

110
00:05:38,614 --> 00:05:40,270
He made it happen.

111
00:05:40,305 --> 00:05:42,300
He took all the manuscripts,
killed a million people but...

112
00:05:42,307 --> 00:05:44,827
- But he left you dumplings.
- He left... yeah.

113
00:05:44,861 --> 00:05:47,036
Mmm, that's awesome.

114
00:05:47,070 --> 00:05:49,038
Yeah, this is what
my soul needed.

115
00:05:49,072 --> 00:05:51,903
Good.

116
00:05:51,937 --> 00:05:54,423
What was it like
coming back the first time?

117
00:05:54,457 --> 00:05:56,286
And how old were you,
and what was it like?

118
00:05:56,321 --> 00:05:57,909
I had a mystical connection

119
00:05:57,943 --> 00:05:59,428
because I had never been
to Armenia.

120
00:05:59,462 --> 00:06:01,775
And we had only read about it
in books per se, you know.

121
00:06:01,809 --> 00:06:04,191
Modern Armenia is different

122
00:06:04,225 --> 00:06:06,538
than what I had thought of,
you know,

123
00:06:06,573 --> 00:06:09,438
because it's thriving,
it's young, you know.

124
00:06:09,472 --> 00:06:13,131
It's got a lot
of interesting dynamics.

125
00:06:13,165 --> 00:06:16,583
And I remember the first time
I flew back to I.A.

126
00:06:16,617 --> 00:06:19,206
the feeling that I got
getting out of the plane

127
00:06:19,240 --> 00:06:21,139
is "Why am I back here?"

128
00:06:21,173 --> 00:06:24,314
Like, it was a weird thing
where it's this...

129
00:06:24,349 --> 00:06:27,145
Inescapable feeling
of kind of the land

130
00:06:27,179 --> 00:06:28,457
having some kind of pull

131
00:06:28,491 --> 00:06:29,906
on your blood
or something like that.

132
00:06:29,941 --> 00:06:32,150
Genealogy, I don't know
what it is.

133
00:06:32,184 --> 00:06:35,567
Do you think that Armenia
looks to the West for anything?

134
00:06:35,602 --> 00:06:36,810
Yes, definitely.

135
00:06:36,844 --> 00:06:38,294
I think, you know, culturally

136
00:06:38,328 --> 00:06:39,709
Armenia is very European.

137
00:06:39,744 --> 00:06:42,402
- Culturally? But...
- Culturally.

138
00:06:42,436 --> 00:06:44,542
Politically, it's very much
tied into Russia.

139
00:06:44,576 --> 00:06:46,475
Not just
as an ex-Soviet republic,

140
00:06:46,509 --> 00:06:48,891
but there's a lot of economic
investment from Russia,

141
00:06:48,925 --> 00:06:52,170
and Russia, obviously, based
on the last two world wars

142
00:06:52,204 --> 00:06:54,483
is extremely... what's the word...

143
00:06:54,517 --> 00:06:57,451
They're very afraid
of their borders, let's say.

144
00:06:57,486 --> 00:06:59,729
Yes, they are
acutely sensitive...

145
00:06:59,764 --> 00:07:03,423
- Acutely sensitive.
- To particularly this area.

146
00:07:09,498 --> 00:07:12,673
There are three million
Armenians living in Armenia,

147
00:07:12,708 --> 00:07:15,780
another eight million
around the world.

148
00:07:15,814 --> 00:07:17,506
Ever since the genocide,

149
00:07:17,540 --> 00:07:21,475
it's been a long, existential
struggle for survival.

150
00:07:21,510 --> 00:07:24,927
Recent history is defined
by three major events...

151
00:07:24,961 --> 00:07:26,998
A massive earthquake in 1988,

152
00:07:27,032 --> 00:07:31,140
followed by the collapse
of the USSR in 1991,

153
00:07:31,174 --> 00:07:35,455
and then a full-scale war
with Azerbaijan in 1992.

154
00:07:35,489 --> 00:07:38,319
Not to mention limited
employment opportunities

155
00:07:38,354 --> 00:07:40,494
and most significantly
its borders,

156
00:07:40,529 --> 00:07:43,221
of which approximately
80% have been closed

157
00:07:43,255 --> 00:07:45,361
due to relationships
with its Turkish

158
00:07:45,395 --> 00:07:47,501
and Azeri neighbors.

159
00:07:47,536 --> 00:07:50,780
Things have not been easy
for Armenians.

160
00:07:53,818 --> 00:07:55,958
♪

161
00:07:55,992 --> 00:07:58,408
On a hillside
overlooking Yerevan sits

162
00:07:58,443 --> 00:08:02,758
a sprawling memorial
to the genocide of 1915.

163
00:08:04,863 --> 00:08:07,797
On the other side of town,
another memorial,

164
00:08:07,832 --> 00:08:11,145
the Yerevan Cascade.

165
00:08:11,180 --> 00:08:14,183
Richard Giragosian
is an American-born professor

166
00:08:14,217 --> 00:08:18,532
and political analyst
who now lives here in Armenia.

167
00:08:18,567 --> 00:08:20,569
How many were lost during this?

168
00:08:20,603 --> 00:08:23,364
Most estimates historically

169
00:08:23,399 --> 00:08:25,850
put it around 1.5 million.

170
00:08:25,884 --> 00:08:27,437
That's a lot of people.

171
00:08:27,472 --> 00:08:30,268
Especially a lot of people
when we look at the per capita,

172
00:08:30,302 --> 00:08:32,442
when we look at the impact
this had.

173
00:08:32,477 --> 00:08:36,343
So, what happened?

174
00:08:36,377 --> 00:08:38,828
In the early 20th Century,

175
00:08:38,863 --> 00:08:40,934
what was historically
western Armenia

176
00:08:40,968 --> 00:08:43,212
was under the control
of the Ottoman Empire,

177
00:08:43,246 --> 00:08:45,041
present day Turkey.

178
00:08:45,076 --> 00:08:48,113
Justifying their actions
by the widely held sentiment

179
00:08:48,148 --> 00:08:50,460
that Christian Armenians
would align themselves

180
00:08:50,495 --> 00:08:52,877
with a hostile
and also Christian Russia,

181
00:08:52,911 --> 00:08:55,189
then undergoing
its second revolution

182
00:08:55,224 --> 00:08:56,950
and threatening their borders,

183
00:08:56,984 --> 00:09:00,125
the Turks rounded up
Armenian intellectuals

184
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:03,059
and summarily executed them.

185
00:09:03,094 --> 00:09:06,615
Military and police units were
dispatched to the countryside

186
00:09:06,649 --> 00:09:09,687
to drive out Armenians
from their villages.

187
00:09:09,721 --> 00:09:12,448
They hanged local leaders
in the town squares,

188
00:09:12,482 --> 00:09:15,140
burned churches,
destroyed manuscripts,

189
00:09:15,175 --> 00:09:18,592
then marched anyone left
towards the Syrian desert,

190
00:09:18,627 --> 00:09:21,664
deliberately starving them
along the way.

191
00:09:23,528 --> 00:09:27,912
Those who survived
scattered across the globe.

192
00:09:27,946 --> 00:09:30,293
They formed large
and vibrant communities

193
00:09:30,328 --> 00:09:32,226
that survive today.

194
00:09:32,261 --> 00:09:34,815
They never forgot the past

195
00:09:34,850 --> 00:09:36,990
and who and what had pushed them

196
00:09:37,024 --> 00:09:38,750
from their homeland.

197
00:09:43,790 --> 00:09:46,102
Let's start with this:
genocide.

198
00:09:46,137 --> 00:09:49,174
Many people seem awfully
and curiously reluctant

199
00:09:49,209 --> 00:09:50,590
to use this word.

200
00:09:50,624 --> 00:09:54,110
As American national
foreign policy,

201
00:09:54,145 --> 00:09:56,009
we use what, "catastrophe"?

202
00:09:56,043 --> 00:09:58,528
Yeah, a "regrettable
series of incidents."

203
00:09:58,563 --> 00:10:00,358
- Yeah, how insulting.
- Yes.

204
00:10:00,392 --> 00:10:01,601
But, I mean, it seems to me,

205
00:10:01,635 --> 00:10:02,947
just as a casual observer,

206
00:10:02,981 --> 00:10:05,846
anytime a state actor
or organization

207
00:10:05,881 --> 00:10:08,504
makes a concerted
and organized effort

208
00:10:08,538 --> 00:10:12,370
to eradicate any ethnic
or national group

209
00:10:12,404 --> 00:10:14,683
that... that's genocide, right?

210
00:10:14,717 --> 00:10:17,375
Yes, what's important
though, however,

211
00:10:17,409 --> 00:10:20,205
is this is our defining issue.

212
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:22,276
This is the unifying issue,

213
00:10:22,311 --> 00:10:23,553
and it's probably in many ways

214
00:10:23,588 --> 00:10:26,764
the only defining issue,
both good and bad.

215
00:10:26,798 --> 00:10:30,215
For Armenians, both Diaspora
and living here?

216
00:10:30,250 --> 00:10:32,390
Yes, it's the fact that, yes,

217
00:10:32,424 --> 00:10:35,704
my grandfather's a survivor,
every family's touched.

218
00:10:35,738 --> 00:10:38,568
But it's not the personal.
It's also the political.

219
00:10:38,603 --> 00:10:41,951
If Turkey wasn't so adamant
about denying

220
00:10:41,986 --> 00:10:43,712
the historical accuracy,

221
00:10:43,746 --> 00:10:46,059
this is what makes it
a living issue,

222
00:10:46,093 --> 00:10:47,405
a present issue.

223
00:10:47,439 --> 00:10:49,234
- Going forward...
- Mmm-hmm?

224
00:10:49,269 --> 00:10:52,341
Do you think there will be
some kind of reconciliation?

225
00:10:52,375 --> 00:10:53,998
Well, I'm
a little more positive.

226
00:10:54,032 --> 00:10:55,724
This is now the turning point,

227
00:10:55,758 --> 00:10:59,037
Armenia looking to normalize
relations with Turkey

228
00:10:59,072 --> 00:11:02,247
not because of the genocide
but despite the genocide.

229
00:11:02,282 --> 00:11:03,593
Do you have any expectation

230
00:11:03,628 --> 00:11:05,734
of fruitful negotiations
with Erdogan?

231
00:11:05,768 --> 00:11:07,805
It seems to me that
things have...

232
00:11:07,839 --> 00:11:09,530
kind of taken a downward turn.

233
00:11:09,565 --> 00:11:12,741
They have, but it was
never supposed to be that easy

234
00:11:12,775 --> 00:11:14,743
or that quick.

235
00:11:14,777 --> 00:11:17,746
We also need to go beyond
victimization

236
00:11:17,780 --> 00:11:22,371
and to take more pride
in survival.

237
00:11:22,405 --> 00:11:24,373
