239
00:12:01,203 --> 00:12:03,619
Lavash, the national bread.

240
00:12:03,653 --> 00:12:07,623
An ever-present feature
of the Armenian table

241
00:12:07,657 --> 00:12:09,556
and a part of everyday life.

242
00:12:11,800 --> 00:12:13,767
Baked on a tonir,

243
00:12:13,802 --> 00:12:15,665
or underground clay oven,

244
00:12:15,700 --> 00:12:20,291
its preparation is passed down
from generation to generation.

245
00:12:26,366 --> 00:12:30,611
Markets like Gum
near the city center

246
00:12:30,646 --> 00:12:32,130
date back to Soviet days,

247
00:12:32,165 --> 00:12:33,822
but they remain a favorite stop

248
00:12:33,856 --> 00:12:36,479
for an older generation
of Armenians.

249
00:12:44,177 --> 00:12:47,283
October brings an array
of seasonal produce,

250
00:12:47,318 --> 00:12:49,458
and Miriam
and her grandmother Leah

251
00:12:49,492 --> 00:12:51,805
pick up ingredients
for a fall tradition...

252
00:12:51,840 --> 00:12:55,222
Ghapama, a rice dish
baked in pumpkin.

253
00:13:01,090 --> 00:13:03,196
The top of the pumpkin
is removed,

254
00:13:03,230 --> 00:13:05,957
and the seeds and pulp
are scraped out.

255
00:13:05,992 --> 00:13:07,925
Dried fruit, almonds, and honey

256
00:13:07,959 --> 00:13:10,997
are mixed with rice
and baked inside.

257
00:13:15,311 --> 00:13:17,866
Incredible.

258
00:13:17,900 --> 00:13:21,386
So, as main course
we prepared Ghapama,

259
00:13:21,421 --> 00:13:22,836
which has its own song.

260
00:13:22,871 --> 00:13:24,804
Serj?

261
00:13:27,565 --> 00:13:30,464
Usually, when you bring in
the dish, you sing it.

262
00:13:30,499 --> 00:13:32,018
We don't cook it very often,

263
00:13:32,052 --> 00:13:33,882
but it's an autumn meal.

264
00:13:33,916 --> 00:13:35,469
We have some pickles there.

265
00:13:35,504 --> 00:13:37,333
We have Armenian cheese there.

266
00:13:37,368 --> 00:13:39,957
And I'm going to serve
Armenian bread.

267
00:13:39,991 --> 00:13:42,373
And this looks like...

268
00:13:42,407 --> 00:13:43,581
It looks like hummus.

269
00:13:43,615 --> 00:13:45,376
- It is hummus.
- That's hummus.

270
00:13:45,410 --> 00:13:46,826
Hummus and bread.

271
00:13:46,860 --> 00:13:47,861
And it's not Armenian.

272
00:13:47,896 --> 00:13:49,725
This is mutabal.

273
00:13:49,759 --> 00:13:51,692
We're not laying any claims
that they're Armenian,

274
00:13:51,727 --> 00:13:53,073
but many western
Armenian families

275
00:13:53,108 --> 00:13:55,213
grow up with this
on the table as well.

276
00:13:55,248 --> 00:13:57,181
Miriam, her mother,
and grandmother

277
00:13:57,215 --> 00:13:59,528
were all born here in Yerevan.

278
00:13:59,562 --> 00:14:02,255
Her husband, Nazareth,
and his family

279
00:14:02,289 --> 00:14:05,258
are more typical
of the diaspora Armenians.

280
00:14:05,292 --> 00:14:08,778
His mom, Nar, was born
in Beirut.

281
00:14:08,813 --> 00:14:11,885
Nazareth, in Toronto.

282
00:14:11,920 --> 00:14:14,508
What language
will your children speak?

283
00:14:14,543 --> 00:14:16,062
Where will they live?

284
00:14:16,096 --> 00:14:18,236
- Here.
- Yeah, here.

285
00:14:18,271 --> 00:14:19,444
No hesitation?

286
00:14:19,479 --> 00:14:21,791
That's the easy question
to answer.

287
00:14:21,826 --> 00:14:23,517
But I think the two of us

288
00:14:23,552 --> 00:14:25,761
would like them to grow up
being equally comfortable

289
00:14:25,795 --> 00:14:27,521
with Armenian, Russian,
and English.

290
00:14:27,556 --> 00:14:30,214
All three languages
are very, very important

291
00:14:30,248 --> 00:14:32,181
for anyone growing up
in Armenia.

292
00:14:32,216 --> 00:14:34,459
They are the two largest
Armenian diasporas,

293
00:14:34,494 --> 00:14:36,427
Russia and America, so.

294
00:14:36,461 --> 00:14:39,568
How many years was it
part of the Soviet Union?

295
00:14:39,602 --> 00:14:43,537
Uh, 70 years, since 1921
more or less until 1991.

296
00:14:43,572 --> 00:14:45,091
So, 70 years.

297
00:14:45,125 --> 00:14:47,852
But what remains of those times?

298
00:15:10,979 --> 00:15:15,293
You sound... wistful
about the old days.

299
00:15:15,328 --> 00:15:18,503
Are things better now or worse?

300
00:15:26,028 --> 00:15:30,308
When Armenia was swallowed up
by the Soviet Union in 1922,

301
00:15:30,343 --> 00:15:34,002
it became the Armenian
Soviet Socialist Republic.

302
00:15:34,036 --> 00:15:36,936
With that came purges
and paranoia

303
00:15:36,970 --> 00:15:38,627
but also a rapid
industrialization,

304
00:15:38,661 --> 00:15:40,836
the evidence of which
is still seen today

305
00:15:40,870 --> 00:15:43,597
in the abandoned factories
and worker's blocks

306
00:15:43,632 --> 00:15:45,634
of another time.

307
00:15:45,668 --> 00:15:49,155
And a Soviet mentality
and sizeable Russian presence

308
00:15:49,189 --> 00:15:52,813
still hang over the country
like a dead weight.

309
00:15:52,848 --> 00:15:57,370
No matter how you felt
about Soviet rule,

310
00:15:57,404 --> 00:16:00,511
the transition was a rough one.

311
00:16:00,545 --> 00:16:03,686
After the collapse
of the USSR in 1991,

312
00:16:03,721 --> 00:16:05,723
Armenia suffered
terrible food shortages

313
00:16:05,757 --> 00:16:07,380
and a ruined electrical grid

314
00:16:07,414 --> 00:16:10,176
that allowed only a couple
of hours of power a day,

315
00:16:10,210 --> 00:16:11,694
if you were lucky.

316
00:16:11,729 --> 00:16:15,491
The worst of those years
would be 1992 to 1994.

317
00:16:15,526 --> 00:16:18,356
But then a few years
after '94 as well.

318
00:16:18,391 --> 00:16:20,041
There was a lot
of pilferage in the beginning.

319
00:16:20,048 --> 00:16:22,705
There was a lot of...
It was dark, dark days.

320
00:16:22,740 --> 00:16:25,674
And the generation
literally learned alphabet

321
00:16:25,708 --> 00:16:27,331
with the candlelight.

322
00:16:27,365 --> 00:16:30,161
Back then, we had only
two hours maybe?

323
00:16:35,925 --> 00:16:37,030
It was something to observe

324
00:16:37,065 --> 00:16:40,033
because during those two hours

325
00:16:40,068 --> 00:16:41,897
someone would go to the balcony

326
00:16:41,931 --> 00:16:43,174
and scream in the yard:

327
00:16:43,209 --> 00:16:45,349
"We have lights,
the electricity is back!"

328
00:16:45,383 --> 00:16:47,730
And everybody would go
do their laundry,

329
00:16:47,765 --> 00:16:49,042
ironing, and cooking.

330
00:16:49,077 --> 00:16:51,527
Everything would be done
in that one hour.

331
00:16:57,947 --> 00:16:59,259
Oh yeah.

332
00:16:59,294 --> 00:17:01,917
But they raised us with love,

333
00:17:01,951 --> 00:17:04,540
and we would play games.

334
00:17:04,575 --> 00:17:07,578
Ma would have her friends
coming over playing guitar.

335
00:17:07,612 --> 00:17:11,202
Looking back, I don't remember
the darkness.

336
00:17:11,237 --> 00:17:12,445
I remember that it was dark,

337
00:17:12,479 --> 00:17:15,448
but emotionally
we didn't feel that.

338
00:17:15,482 --> 00:17:18,934
Parents, grandparents
really did their best

339
00:17:18,968 --> 00:17:20,763
for kids not to feel
the darkness.

340
00:17:20,798 --> 00:17:23,628
It was heroism on their part.

341
00:17:23,663 --> 00:17:24,871
Especially in the winter.

342
00:17:24,905 --> 00:17:26,528
Especially the winter.

343
00:17:26,562 --> 00:17:29,117
But also I think we're observing

344
00:17:29,151 --> 00:17:31,981
a very interesting period
of our history

345
00:17:32,016 --> 00:17:34,605
when change is happening.

346
00:17:34,639 --> 00:17:36,607
Little by little,
and it's us to make.

347
00:17:36,641 --> 00:17:38,471
Right, Serj?

348
00:17:49,585 --> 00:17:51,139
♪

349
00:18:14,196 --> 00:18:15,680
The Tumo Center

350
00:18:15,715 --> 00:18:17,993
is an after-school program
for kids.

351
00:18:18,027 --> 00:18:19,857
You get to pick your course
of study,

352
00:18:19,891 --> 00:18:23,585
be it art, technology,
creative writing, whatever.

353
00:18:23,619 --> 00:18:25,000
There are no grades,

354
00:18:25,034 --> 00:18:27,658
no mandatory
course requirements,

355
00:18:27,692 --> 00:18:29,625
and upwards of 14,000 kids
are enrolled

356
00:18:29,660 --> 00:18:32,007
at four locations
across Armenia.

357
00:18:32,041 --> 00:18:34,768
It's free,
an entirely non-profit,

358
00:18:34,803 --> 00:18:36,356
privately funded venture,

359
00:18:36,391 --> 00:18:39,911
an investment in the youth
of a young country.

360
00:18:54,305 --> 00:18:55,893
The main goal is

361
00:18:55,927 --> 00:18:59,966
to complement
their formal education.

362
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:02,210
The curriculum is not mandatory.

363
00:19:02,244 --> 00:19:04,384
You pick what you want.

364
00:19:04,419 --> 00:19:05,834
You can pick music,

365
00:19:05,868 --> 00:19:09,217
graphic design, 3D modeling,

366
00:19:09,251 --> 00:19:11,046
or programming, games,

367
00:19:11,080 --> 00:19:14,222
whatever, photography, robotics.

368
00:19:14,256 --> 00:19:17,017
The managing director,
Maria Lou Papazian,

369
00:19:17,052 --> 00:19:19,744
and her husband Pegor
are two former members

370
00:19:19,779 --> 00:19:22,230
of the Armenian Diaspora,

371
00:19:22,264 --> 00:19:24,404
both extraordinary
but not unusual

372
00:19:24,439 --> 00:19:25,854
in the new Armenia.

373
00:19:25,888 --> 00:19:28,097
They're not ex-pats but re-pats,

374
00:19:28,132 --> 00:19:29,996
people who though not born here

375
00:19:30,030 --> 00:19:33,102
have chosen to come home
and help build a nation.

376
00:19:33,137 --> 00:19:34,828
Well, we grew up
together in Beirut

377
00:19:34,863 --> 00:19:36,416
then moved to the States.

378
00:19:36,451 --> 00:19:38,073
And the reason we moved

379
00:19:38,107 --> 00:19:40,317
was because of
the Armenian thing.

380
00:19:40,351 --> 00:19:41,939
Our kid was growing up,

381
00:19:41,973 --> 00:19:45,770
so we told our friends
we're gonna move,

382
00:19:45,805 --> 00:19:47,190
we need him to go
to Armenian school.

383
00:19:47,220 --> 00:19:48,720
So they said,
"You're going to Armenia?"

384
00:19:48,739 --> 00:19:51,914
I said,
"No, Glendale, California."

385
00:19:51,949 --> 00:19:54,572
But, eventually,
we did move here, 12 years ago.

386
00:19:54,607 --> 00:19:56,264
Living in Glendale

387
00:19:56,298 --> 00:19:57,955
and keeping always saying

388
00:19:57,989 --> 00:20:00,129
you have to keep your identity

389
00:20:00,164 --> 00:20:02,097
was strange.

390
00:20:02,131 --> 00:20:05,963
And every time coming up
with stories for the kids,

391
00:20:05,997 --> 00:20:07,965
you have to love your country,

392
00:20:07,999 --> 00:20:10,554
you're Armenian,
you have to speak Armenian.

393
00:20:10,588 --> 00:20:12,038
Whereas once you're here,

394
00:20:12,072 --> 00:20:13,626
you just forget all about that,

395
00:20:13,660 --> 00:20:16,249
and it's more about being
a good person,

396
00:20:16,284 --> 00:20:18,458
having ambitions, all of that.

397
00:20:18,493 --> 00:20:20,046
And the Armenian part,

398
00:20:20,080 --> 00:20:21,979
you can let that
happen naturally.

399
00:20:22,013 --> 00:20:27,881
Apricot vodka
is a good start to a meal.

400
00:20:27,916 --> 00:20:30,367
Gyan is local favorite,

401
00:20:30,401 --> 00:20:33,301
a restaurant operating out of
what was once a private home,

402
00:20:33,335 --> 00:20:35,993
something of a throwback
to Soviet days

403
00:20:36,027 --> 00:20:38,651
like the Cuban paladars,
when private enterprise,

404
00:20:38,685 --> 00:20:41,309
not to mention the spending
of money on entertainment,

405
00:20:41,343 --> 00:20:46,141
could be frowned on,
and privacy was at a premium.

406
00:20:48,212 --> 00:20:52,837
Trout wrapped and baked
in lavash.

407
00:20:52,872 --> 00:20:55,668
This is not light cooking.

408
00:21:01,881 --> 00:21:04,021
There's certain things

409
00:21:04,055 --> 00:21:06,506
about especially maybe
the last 20, 30 years

410
00:21:06,541 --> 00:21:08,301
of the Soviet Union, '60s on,

411
00:21:08,336 --> 00:21:11,856
that not the brutal, early
Bolshevik Stalinist times

412
00:21:11,891 --> 00:21:14,618
but later on were,
in terms of investment

413
00:21:14,652 --> 00:21:15,964
and culture and education...

414
00:21:15,998 --> 00:21:17,931
Well, I mean, it's very much

415
00:21:17,966 --> 00:21:19,692
a legacy of the Soviet Union.

416
00:21:19,726 --> 00:21:22,281
Armenia was kind of
a nerd republic in a way.

417
00:21:22,315 --> 00:21:24,697
They specialized
in different republics,

418
00:21:24,731 --> 00:21:27,216
and Armenia was where
they concentrated

419
00:21:27,251 --> 00:21:31,359
science, technology,
particle accelerator,

420
00:21:31,393 --> 00:21:33,671
radio telescope, all of that.

421
00:21:33,706 --> 00:21:35,708
And so we benefitted from that,

422
00:21:35,742 --> 00:21:37,641
and you see a lot of
Armenians attributing that

423
00:21:37,675 --> 00:21:39,332
to our "genes" and so on.

424
00:21:39,367 --> 00:21:43,060
But, of course, our genes
are the same as anyone else's.

425
00:21:43,094 --> 00:21:45,683
It's the culture that...
Right.

426
00:21:45,718 --> 00:21:47,264
You know, you take
the good with the bad,

427
00:21:47,271 --> 00:21:50,723
and the good is we're
a cerebral nation in a way.

428
00:21:50,757 --> 00:21:52,656
That's how we grew up.
We like chess.

429
00:21:52,690 --> 00:21:55,141
We're like we're nerds.

430
00:22:18,889 --> 00:22:21,926
Armenia enjoyed
a somewhat celebrated status

431
00:22:21,961 --> 00:22:23,480
during Soviet times,

432
00:22:23,514 --> 00:22:26,345
and Russian influence
is everywhere still.

433
00:22:26,379 --> 00:22:28,347
Chess is taught
in public schools,

434
00:22:28,381 --> 00:22:30,279
a basic life skill.

435
00:22:30,314 --> 00:22:34,249
It's probably the fact that
Armenia was such a powerhouse

436
00:22:34,283 --> 00:22:36,596
of smart, highly educated
brainiacs

437
00:22:36,631 --> 00:22:39,116
with strong backgrounds
in engineering, math,

438
00:22:39,150 --> 00:22:41,256
rocketry, and technology,

439
00:22:41,290 --> 00:22:44,224
a veritable Silicon Valley
of the Caucuses

440
00:22:44,259 --> 00:22:48,436
that largely spared them
the worst of Soviet rule,

441
00:22:48,470 --> 00:22:51,370
and also perhaps the reason
that it continues

442
00:22:51,404 --> 00:22:53,406
to be a leader in IT.

443
00:22:53,441 --> 00:22:56,720
I meet a few members
from the tech community

444
00:22:56,754 --> 00:22:59,136
at a local brewery in Yerevan...

445
00:22:59,170 --> 00:23:02,035
Arthur, an industry writer,

446
00:23:02,070 --> 00:23:04,969
Harot, a software engineer,

447
00:23:05,004 --> 00:23:07,455
and Ruben, a cyber security
consultant.

448
00:23:07,489 --> 00:23:09,940
So what are you making?

449
00:23:09,974 --> 00:23:11,459
What is coming of this?

450
00:23:11,493 --> 00:23:14,427
IT is a big...

451
00:23:14,462 --> 00:23:16,325
- For the country.
- It's a big house.

452
00:23:16,360 --> 00:23:18,051
So, websites,

453
00:23:18,086 --> 00:23:19,881
web based stuff and chip design.

454
00:23:19,915 --> 00:23:21,779
We're all over the place
actually.

455
00:23:21,814 --> 00:23:23,609
But this comes
from the old times, you know.

456
00:23:23,643 --> 00:23:25,438
Like, in Soviet times
what happened is

457
00:23:25,473 --> 00:23:27,095
they manufactured chips,

458
00:23:27,129 --> 00:23:29,166
lots of electronic stuff for...

459
00:23:29,200 --> 00:23:31,340
I heard for Soviet submarines.

460
00:23:31,375 --> 00:23:33,446
But actually it was

461
00:23:33,481 --> 00:23:36,484
a success story
in the Soviet time.

462
00:23:36,518 --> 00:23:38,347
You can have a success story

463
00:23:38,382 --> 00:23:41,143
if you were
a Communist Party official

464
00:23:41,178 --> 00:23:44,008
or if you were doing science.

465
00:23:44,043 --> 00:23:45,941
Or perhaps artist,
and that's it.

466
00:23:45,976 --> 00:23:50,014
And the science was
the most clean career.

467
00:23:50,049 --> 00:23:53,293
I mean, you were not
compromising your own beliefs,

468
00:23:53,328 --> 00:23:55,364
and you were
doing something good.

469
00:23:55,399 --> 00:23:58,816
If you were to imagine
the perfect business

470
00:23:58,851 --> 00:24:01,819
and the most efficient export
for a land-locked nation

471
00:24:01,854 --> 00:24:04,028
with most of its borders closed,

472
00:24:04,063 --> 00:24:06,686
it would be
information technology, right?

473
00:24:06,721 --> 00:24:08,999
Or, to put it simply, brains.

474
00:24:09,033 --> 00:24:11,829
They teach chess in school?
Yes.

475
00:24:11,864 --> 00:24:15,833
In school?
Starting at what age?

476
00:24:15,868 --> 00:24:17,386
Third grade.
My son hates it, he's...

477
00:24:17,421 --> 00:24:19,112
No, second grade.

478
00:24:19,147 --> 00:24:22,391
- So everybody plays chess?
- Yeah, you kind of...

479
00:24:22,426 --> 00:24:24,670
That already is
a very different...

480
00:24:24,704 --> 00:24:25,981
I have a ranking actually.

481
00:24:26,016 --> 00:24:27,776
Really? I didn't know.
Come on.

482
00:24:27,811 --> 00:24:29,502
Small number.

483
00:24:29,537 --> 00:24:32,609
But that's a very different
mentality than most places.

484
00:24:32,643 --> 00:24:36,026
Actually, my mom
took me to chess class.

485
00:24:36,060 --> 00:24:37,959
It was not because
of the country's

486
00:24:37,993 --> 00:24:39,892
like a super nation in chess
or something.

487
00:24:39,926 --> 00:24:42,135
Just she wanted to take me
some place

488
00:24:42,170 --> 00:24:45,345
where, like, I can develop
my brains.

489
00:24:45,380 --> 00:24:48,176
But, actually,
there's a quick answer.

490
00:24:48,210 --> 00:24:50,419
When you are being oppressed

491
00:24:50,454 --> 00:24:52,076
during your history,

492
00:24:52,111 --> 00:24:55,563
knowledge is something
that cannot be taken off you.

493
00:24:55,597 --> 00:24:59,083
Anything can happen.
Soviet Union can collapse.

494
00:24:59,118 --> 00:25:02,017
There can be pogroms.
There can be immigration.

495
00:25:02,052 --> 00:25:05,434
They can take your home.
They can take your fortune.

496
00:25:05,469 --> 00:25:07,333
But knowledge and skill
is something

497
00:25:07,367 --> 00:25:10,543
that remains with you
for all of the time.

498
00:25:10,578 --> 00:25:14,582
And that's why Armenians
are investing in education,

499
00:25:14,616 --> 00:25:16,515
in knowledge, in skill,

500
00:25:16,549 --> 00:25:19,276
to invest in the development
of a child.

501
00:25:19,310 --> 00:25:24,833
All of us are children
that were invested in.

502
00:25:24,868 --> 00:25:29,113
The knowledge is something
that you always keep with you.

503
00:25:29,148 --> 00:25:33,532
I think this explains a lot.

504
00:25:47,822 --> 00:25:50,203
My trip to the disputed,

505
00:25:50,238 --> 00:25:52,758
Armenian-controlled enclave
of Nagorno-Karabakh

506
00:25:52,792 --> 00:25:55,381
requires an early morning stop
at a military base

507
00:25:55,415 --> 00:25:57,383
on the outskirts of Yerevan.

508
00:25:57,417 --> 00:26:01,214
And, apparently,
a flight in this thing,

509
00:26:01,249 --> 00:26:04,770
a smoking, flame-belching,
banged-up looking

510
00:26:04,804 --> 00:26:07,289
Soviet Mi-8 twin turbine chopper

511
00:26:07,324 --> 00:26:09,602
whose appearance
prior to boarding

512
00:26:09,637 --> 00:26:12,398
does not fill me
with confidence.

513
00:26:20,337 --> 00:26:23,236
But, once up in the air,

514
00:26:23,271 --> 00:26:26,446
it takes me over crags
and peaks and steppes

515
00:26:26,481 --> 00:26:28,414
across the international
recognized border

516
00:26:28,448 --> 00:26:30,002
with Azerbaijan

517
00:26:30,036 --> 00:26:33,074
to what the Armenians
call Arstakh,

518
00:26:33,108 --> 00:26:36,905
an isolated pocket
surrounded on all sides

519
00:26:36,940 --> 00:26:39,080
by Azeris.

520
00:26:39,114 --> 00:26:42,083
Whose mountains these are

521
00:26:42,117 --> 00:26:45,811
is a subject of contention
and conflict to say the least.

522
00:26:45,845 --> 00:26:48,607
When the borders of
the South Caucasus were drawn

523
00:26:48,641 --> 00:26:52,024
by the Russian conquerors
some 200 years ago,

524
00:26:52,058 --> 00:26:53,646
a strong Russian presence
kept ethnic

525
00:26:53,681 --> 00:26:55,683
and religious rivalries
in check.

526
00:26:55,717 --> 00:26:58,340
But, whenever disorder
hit Russia,

527
00:26:58,375 --> 00:26:59,997
war has broken out here.

528
00:27:00,032 --> 00:27:03,483
Most recently, after the fall
of the USSR.

529
00:27:06,590 --> 00:27:08,488
The brutal conflict
went largely ignored

530
00:27:08,523 --> 00:27:10,214
internationally.

531
00:27:10,249 --> 00:27:11,664
As with any war,

532
00:27:11,699 --> 00:27:13,459
particularly wars with an ethnic

533
00:27:13,493 --> 00:27:15,668
or religious component
over territory,

534
00:27:15,703 --> 00:27:17,670
it was ugly, murderous,

535
00:27:17,705 --> 00:27:21,812
and with atrocities
committed by both sides.

536
00:27:21,847 --> 00:27:25,057
1992 was a turning point.

537
00:27:25,091 --> 00:27:27,784
The Armenians organized
and created their own army

538
00:27:27,818 --> 00:27:29,786
and, surprising everyone,
pushed through

539
00:27:29,820 --> 00:27:32,064
and took full control
of Karabakh

540
00:27:32,098 --> 00:27:34,583
and the surrounding areas.

541
00:27:34,618 --> 00:27:37,483
These buffer zones
are ethnically Azeri

542
00:27:37,517 --> 00:27:38,898
and bitterly contested

543
00:27:38,933 --> 00:27:41,798
and the subject
of continuing dispute.

544
00:27:41,832 --> 00:27:44,490
There are still
violent confrontations,

545
00:27:44,524 --> 00:27:47,044
the latest being
a four-day battle

546
00:27:47,079 --> 00:27:49,875
in the Spring of 2016.

547
00:27:49,909 --> 00:27:52,153
Russia's role in the conflict

548
00:27:52,187 --> 00:27:54,017
is suspiciously cynical.

549
00:27:54,051 --> 00:27:58,159
They actively arm, support,
and advise both sides

550
00:27:58,193 --> 00:27:59,988
as it appears in their interest

551
00:28:00,023 --> 00:28:04,061
that there be
no lasting resolution.

552
00:28:04,096 --> 00:28:04,596
♪

553
00:28:08,203 --> 00:28:10,447
Travel to this region
continues to be

554
00:28:10,481 --> 00:28:12,345
a particularly sensitive issue,

555
00:28:12,380 --> 00:28:14,589
especially for the Azeris.

556
00:28:14,623 --> 00:28:16,695
Simply by coming here,
I've become,

557
00:28:16,729 --> 00:28:19,283
as I read in the papers
a few days later,

558
00:28:19,318 --> 00:28:24,012
officially persona non grata
in Azerbaijan.

559
00:28:24,047 --> 00:28:28,603
Stepanakert is the capital
of the autonomous republic

560
00:28:28,637 --> 00:28:31,744
of Nagorno-Karabakh.

561
00:28:31,779 --> 00:28:36,231
And overlooking it,
the village of Shushi.

562
00:28:44,964 --> 00:28:48,761
Zhingalov Khats is
a specialty of the region.

563
00:28:48,796 --> 00:28:52,040
This lavash bread is stuffed
with greens and onions

564
00:28:52,075 --> 00:28:55,630
before being toasted
atop a cast-iron sheet.

565
00:29:02,913 --> 00:29:06,745
Khorovats... basically,
Armenian barbecue.

566
00:29:06,779 --> 00:29:08,229
Meat on a stick,

567
00:29:08,263 --> 00:29:11,611
which is... let's face it...
Always good.

568
00:29:14,442 --> 00:29:17,756
Khorovats.

569
00:29:17,790 --> 00:29:21,311
Armenians try sometimes
to cook it.

570
00:29:21,345 --> 00:29:25,004
Not the same thing.

571
00:29:25,039 --> 00:29:26,661
Armenia and Karabakh,

572
00:29:26,695 --> 00:29:29,146
two different things
or the same?

573
00:29:29,181 --> 00:29:32,011
Not really. Karabakh is...

574
00:29:32,046 --> 00:29:34,255
definitely part of
the Armenian civilization,

575
00:29:34,289 --> 00:29:36,084
the Armenian culture.

576
00:29:36,119 --> 00:29:37,776
I wouldn't separate them.

577
00:29:37,810 --> 00:29:40,468
I think Karabakh is
part of Armenia

578
00:29:40,502 --> 00:29:42,642
but not part of
the Republic of Armenia.

579
00:29:42,677 --> 00:29:44,921
It's like a continuation
of Armenia.

580
00:29:44,955 --> 00:29:46,094
We are the same.

581
00:29:46,129 --> 00:29:47,924
Tegran served in the military

582
00:29:47,958 --> 00:29:51,168
and is now is Karabakh's
only opposition party.

583
00:29:51,203 --> 00:29:52,791
Tatool is a journalist.

584
00:29:52,825 --> 00:29:55,207
Saro, our host, is Armenian

585
00:29:55,241 --> 00:29:56,864
but born in Azerbaijan,

586
00:29:56,898 --> 00:29:59,142
having fled during the war.

587
00:29:59,176 --> 00:30:01,938
He now runs a guest house
here in Shushi.

588
00:30:01,972 --> 00:30:05,734
To what extent is this
just a religious conflict?

589
00:30:05,769 --> 00:30:07,074
- No, it's not really.
- Not at all?

590
00:30:07,081 --> 00:30:10,360
- No, no, no, no. Nothing...
- No, no.

591
00:30:10,394 --> 00:30:12,155
This is a Christian island.

592
00:30:12,189 --> 00:30:14,640
Well, this is
Christian island, it's true.

593
00:30:14,674 --> 00:30:15,848
This is Christian island.

594
00:30:15,883 --> 00:30:18,402
But the conflict
of Nagorno-Karabakh

595
00:30:18,437 --> 00:30:19,887
is not religious.

596
00:30:19,921 --> 00:30:22,303
There are people here,
hardliners here,

597
00:30:22,337 --> 00:30:24,823
who refer to Azeris as Turks.

598
00:30:24,857 --> 00:30:26,894
- But they are Turks.
- They are Turks.

599
00:30:26,928 --> 00:30:30,138
- They are Turks, yes.
- Please explain.

600
00:30:30,173 --> 00:30:33,901
I think probably they are
not ident...

601
00:30:33,935 --> 00:30:36,558
They do not bear
historical responsibility

602
00:30:36,593 --> 00:30:39,044
for the actions committed
by the Ottomans.

603
00:30:39,078 --> 00:30:42,254
But the struggle of
the people Nagorno-Karabakh

604
00:30:42,288 --> 00:30:46,051
for their existence is
continuation of the struggle

605
00:30:46,085 --> 00:30:49,261
of Armenian people
to live peacefully on...

606
00:30:49,295 --> 00:30:51,228
In their historical homeland.

607
00:30:51,263 --> 00:30:54,335
I'm not saying that
Azeris and Turks

608
00:30:54,369 --> 00:30:55,784
are the same nations.

609
00:30:55,819 --> 00:30:56,882
But they are Turk nations...

610
00:30:56,889 --> 00:30:58,891
They're working in unison.

611
00:30:58,926 --> 00:31:02,239
Yeah, they're working
in unity today

612
00:31:02,274 --> 00:31:04,000
to isolate Armenia.

613
00:31:04,034 --> 00:31:05,760
Do you think there's a sense

614
00:31:05,794 --> 00:31:07,935
that when people
look at this conflict

615
00:31:07,969 --> 00:31:10,213
they think they look back
and they say

616
00:31:10,247 --> 00:31:11,870
this is what could happen
in the future?

617
00:31:11,904 --> 00:31:13,112
Yeah, absolutely.

618
00:31:13,147 --> 00:31:15,735
It is absolutely
an existential conflict.

619
00:31:15,770 --> 00:31:18,704
If we lose, we know
that we will be destroyed.

620
00:31:18,738 --> 00:31:22,294
Who will help?
Who cares?

621
00:31:22,328 --> 00:31:23,364
Support?

622
00:31:23,398 --> 00:31:24,434
Who will support you

623
00:31:24,468 --> 00:31:26,539
if things once again get ugly?

624
00:31:26,574 --> 00:31:27,740
What do you think the future...

625
00:31:27,747 --> 00:31:29,646
- No one, no one. We.
- No one?

626
00:31:29,680 --> 00:31:32,131
I think there is
a clear understanding

627
00:31:32,166 --> 00:31:33,270
in Armenian society

628
00:31:33,305 --> 00:31:36,032
that we can only rely
on ourselves.

629
00:31:36,066 --> 00:31:38,724
But another reality
is we are paying

630
00:31:38,758 --> 00:31:40,036
very, very high price.

631
00:31:40,070 --> 00:31:44,385
Since 1994, Armenian
and Karabakh sides

632
00:31:44,419 --> 00:31:48,078
lost about 3,000 soldiers.

633
00:31:48,113 --> 00:31:54,429
We are losing our 18,
20 year old sons, you know.

634
00:31:54,464 --> 00:31:56,259
This is sad reality.

635
00:31:56,293 --> 00:32:00,815
And I don't know how
will this situation continue.

636
00:32:00,849 --> 00:32:02,334
I don't know.

637
00:32:02,368 --> 00:32:06,234
I think it's the right time
to drink for peace.

638
00:32:06,269 --> 00:32:08,409
For peace, yeah.

639
00:32:08,443 --> 00:32:09,479
You read my mind now.

640
00:32:09,513 --> 00:32:12,620
So, cheers.

641
00:32:12,654 --> 00:32:13,932
Cheers.

642
00:32:20,214 --> 00:32:20,714
♪

643
00:32:41,200 --> 00:32:45,446
It's a 3 1/2 hour train ride
from the capital to Gyumri,

644
00:32:45,480 --> 00:32:48,863
Armenia's second largest city.

645
00:32:58,769 --> 00:33:01,117
Gyumri was at the near epicenter

646
00:33:01,151 --> 00:33:02,981
of the magnitude 7.0
earthquake

647
00:33:03,015 --> 00:33:07,502
that absolutely devastated
much of the country in 1988,

648
00:33:07,537 --> 00:33:09,711
killing 25,000 people

649
00:33:09,746 --> 00:33:12,887
and displacing hundreds
of thousands more.

650
00:33:12,921 --> 00:33:14,993
Recovery was made more difficult

651
00:33:15,027 --> 00:33:17,754
by the subsequent collapse
of the Soviet Union

652
00:33:17,788 --> 00:33:19,411
and the Karabakh war.

653
00:33:19,445 --> 00:33:21,930
Manufacturing, infrastructure,

654
00:33:21,965 --> 00:33:25,382
the country's industrial base
and political stability

655
00:33:25,417 --> 00:33:29,869
all crumbled
along with the buildings.

656
00:33:32,389 --> 00:33:34,391
The cemetery
on the way into town

657
00:33:34,426 --> 00:33:36,083
gives you a powerful reminder

658
00:33:36,117 --> 00:33:38,050
of how many died.

659
00:33:38,085 --> 00:33:41,674
One tombstone after another
after another,

660
00:33:41,709 --> 00:33:44,574
all dating back
to the same year.

661
00:33:55,999 --> 00:34:01,867
Poloz Mukuch sits
on a recently rebuilt street.

662
00:34:01,901 --> 00:34:05,422
Inside, I meet with
three young Gyumritzi

663
00:34:05,457 --> 00:34:07,976
determined to rebuild
and revitalize

664
00:34:08,011 --> 00:34:10,255
their city and their country.

665
00:34:10,289 --> 00:34:12,912
Anush works for
an equal rights NGO

666
00:34:12,947 --> 00:34:14,535
back in Yerevan.

667
00:34:14,569 --> 00:34:19,229
Amalia is in tech,
and Gayan works in tourism.

668
00:34:19,264 --> 00:34:21,645
So were you all born here?

669
00:34:21,680 --> 00:34:23,820
- Yes.
- Born in this city.

670
00:34:23,854 --> 00:34:27,306
But two of you live here.
Who doesn't live here?

671
00:34:27,341 --> 00:34:29,067
I live in Yerevan.

672
00:34:29,101 --> 00:34:30,447
You live in Yerevan now.

673
00:34:30,482 --> 00:34:32,898
I have lived in Yerevan
for four years,

674
00:34:32,932 --> 00:34:35,280
and that's the beauty
of my story.

675
00:34:35,314 --> 00:34:36,936
Then I came back.

676
00:34:36,971 --> 00:34:40,457
It doesn't matter
how it was hard to suffer here.

677
00:34:40,492 --> 00:34:43,081
Me, my family, my father,

678
00:34:43,115 --> 00:34:45,428
we never thought
to leave the city.

679
00:34:45,462 --> 00:34:47,982
And that's why for me
Gyumri history

680
00:34:48,016 --> 00:34:50,812
is divided into two parts.

681
00:34:50,847 --> 00:34:52,780
Like, before earthquake

682
00:34:52,814 --> 00:34:55,783
the nice story
I heard from my parents,

683
00:34:55,817 --> 00:34:57,267
and after the earthquake

684
00:34:57,302 --> 00:35:00,339
the difficulties
and hard times we had.

685
00:35:00,374 --> 00:35:03,135
But also the renaissance

686
00:35:03,170 --> 00:35:05,310
that now the city is changing

687
00:35:05,344 --> 00:35:07,864
because the generation
is changing.

688
00:35:09,969 --> 00:35:13,421
This is...
This is some typical soup.

689
00:35:13,456 --> 00:35:16,666
Oxtail? Oxtail soup, yeah.

690
00:35:16,700 --> 00:35:19,255
It should be a little spicy.

691
00:35:19,289 --> 00:35:20,497
- Good.
- Yeah.

692
00:35:20,532 --> 00:35:23,259
And this is liver and heart?

693
00:35:23,293 --> 00:35:24,329
- Yes.
- Delicious.

694
00:35:24,363 --> 00:35:27,159
With tomato and oil.

695
00:35:27,194 --> 00:35:28,885
This, what's this dish called?

696
00:35:28,919 --> 00:35:30,707
I mean, I know what it is,
it's a sheep's head but...

697
00:35:30,714 --> 00:35:32,647
- Yes.
- This is called "kalleh."

698
00:35:32,682 --> 00:35:35,340
- "Kalleh." Kalleh.
- In the local language.

699
00:35:35,374 --> 00:35:37,376
When I was kid,
I remember my father

700
00:35:37,411 --> 00:35:40,172
not only went
to restaurant with kalleh,

701
00:35:40,207 --> 00:35:41,863
but he brought it home for us.

702
00:35:41,898 --> 00:35:43,348
- Oh yeah?
- And I was afraid.

703
00:35:43,382 --> 00:35:45,902
I was afraid of the teeth.
Yeah.

704
00:35:45,936 --> 00:35:49,630
Actually, you got
the good part there.

705
00:35:49,664 --> 00:35:52,288
Yeah.

706
00:35:52,322 --> 00:35:53,875
So, let me ask this.

707
00:35:53,910 --> 00:35:58,846
Technology not just here
but Armenia in general

708
00:35:58,880 --> 00:36:02,677
seems to be the major hope
for the future.

709
00:36:02,712 --> 00:36:06,854
What do you think the city
will be like in 20 years?

710
00:36:06,888 --> 00:36:11,203
You know, the history
is not a stable thing

711
00:36:11,238 --> 00:36:13,378
that we can count on.

712
00:36:13,412 --> 00:36:15,656
But what I see 10 years ago
and 10 years now

713
00:36:15,690 --> 00:36:17,830
Gyumri is developing quite fast.

714
00:36:17,865 --> 00:36:20,212
It's really good.
I see really good developments.

715
00:36:20,247 --> 00:36:24,527
And I can say that's mostly due
to the younger generation.

716
00:36:24,561 --> 00:36:26,114
I would definitely say that.

717
00:36:26,149 --> 00:36:29,428
It's self-employment
and entrepreneurship

718
00:36:29,463 --> 00:36:31,775
that is developing
among the youth

719
00:36:31,810 --> 00:36:35,607
very, very in a very kind of
fast way these days.

720
00:36:35,641 --> 00:36:38,782
Because people understand
that if you stay in Gyumri

721
00:36:38,817 --> 00:36:41,199
you need to create
your own stuff.

722
00:36:41,233 --> 00:36:43,408
We never should stop.

723
00:36:43,442 --> 00:36:44,754
We never should wait for others

724
00:36:44,788 --> 00:36:47,274
to help our city and ourselves.

725
00:36:47,308 --> 00:36:49,241
We should think,
we should create,

726
00:36:49,276 --> 00:36:51,519
we should use our strong sides

727
00:36:51,554 --> 00:36:53,728
to move forward.

728
00:37:05,947 --> 00:37:07,259
♪

729
00:37:13,645 --> 00:37:15,267
The GAZ M21 Volga

730
00:37:15,302 --> 00:37:18,891
Executive Class four-door sedan.

731
00:37:18,926 --> 00:37:22,274
Don't mind us.
We're just Volga'ing.

732
00:37:22,309 --> 00:37:25,173
The ultimate
is Soviet driving luxury.

733
00:37:28,832 --> 00:37:31,456
Corinthian leather, nice.
Yeah.

734
00:37:36,184 --> 00:37:38,463
Wonder what top speed
on this thing is.

735
00:37:38,497 --> 00:37:40,327
I don't want to wonder.

736
00:37:40,361 --> 00:37:41,949
The decelerator
isn't that great.

737
00:37:41,983 --> 00:37:43,433
Right.

738
00:37:43,468 --> 00:37:46,643
Only an hour's drive
from the capital

739
00:37:46,678 --> 00:37:48,024
sits Lake Sevan

740
00:37:48,058 --> 00:37:52,408
in some beautiful countryside.

741
00:37:52,442 --> 00:37:54,824
So it's the Switzerland
of Armenia?

742
00:37:54,858 --> 00:37:56,860
Dilijan is the Switzerland
of Armenia.

743
00:37:56,895 --> 00:37:59,173
It's one of
my favorite spots actually.

744
00:37:59,207 --> 00:38:00,933
What am I eating today?

745
